Bloomberg: Venezuela has bitcoins hidden and doesn't know what to do with them
Venezuela's central bank is conducting internal tests to determine whether it can hold cryptocurrencies. It responds to the direction from state-owned company Petróleos de Venezuela (PDVSA), which seeks to be able to send bitcoin and ethery to the central bank and then pay the bank to cryptocurrencies' suppliers of the oil firm. Employees are also studying a proposal to allow the central bank to count cryptocurrencies in foreign exchange reserves, which are now close to a minimum in 30 years. Citing information from four sources, Bloomberg reported.
The sanctions imposed by the United States on the authoritarian regime of President Nicolás Maduro largely cut off Venezuela from the global financial system. This has further deepened the economic crisis in the country. Meanwhile, the current crisis is one of the most serious in comparison globally, forcing officials to use a mixture of different ways of moving money. While Maduro's efforts to launch the world's first state cryptocurrency failed, continued efforts to exploit digital currencies show how desperately the government is trying to find ways to circumvent restrictions.
Neither Venezuela's Central Bank nor PDVSA responded to the request for comment.
It is unclear how PDVSA came to its own bitcoin and ethers, nor how much of the value of these currencies it owns. The company has problems getting payments from customers by conventional channels, as the big banks are unwilling to trade with the sanctioned entities. Last month, the company received most of its $700 million ($16.6 billion) payment in Chinese yuan because the parties failed to find financial institutions to make the transaction possible.
PDVSA may not be keen to sell cryptocurrencies on the open market, as this would require it to register on the stock market and submit to an in-depth inspection, the so-called due diligence. Instead, he wants the cryptocurrency to be used by the central bank and paid with it to the entities to which PDVSA owes. Officials at the oil firm believe that the central bank is less exposed to any obstacles that could arise when paying cryptocurrencies.
Bitcoins and ethers are used to verify and record transactions by a decentralised online ledger known as blockchain. In some cases, relatively anonymous transfers are made possible without the need for a middleman. Few banks are involved in digital currencies because of problems with money laundering and client information related to them and complicating compliance with the regulations.
Cryptocurrencies after the 2018 debacle are experiencing a return to the limelight this year, owing to the expectation of their greater adoption by the institutions and the company's plan to come up with its own cryptocurrency. They still remain unstable. Bitcoin has fallen almost 20 percent in the last four days, but has a profit of about 130 percent since the start of the year.
