The library commemorates the anniversary of the death of Wenceslas IV with a manuscript exhibition
Six rare historical manuscripts from the turn of the 14th and 15th centuries, from the time of the Roman and Czech King Wenceslas IV, can be seen today and on Saturday by people in Klementinum, Prague. The National Library released them from its vaults to commemorate this year's 600th anniversary of Wenceslas' death. This morning, librarians and restorers placed the rare originals in the showcases in the Mirror Chapel. Admission to the exhibition is free of charge, it is open both days from 10:00 to 18:00.
The exhibition of documents called Ad mandatum domini Regis: From the Royal Office and the Wenceslaus IV Library, the library was prepared together with the National Archives. The written heritage from the reign of Václav IV is viewed by the National Archives from the point of view of official documents and the National Library from the point of view of literary works, its author Jan Vojtíšek said of the exhibition.
"Visitors can look forward, for example, to a work on the agriculture of Peter de Crescentiis, which is basically a kind of encyclopedia of agriculture, or a breviary, a prayer book by one of the Benedictines of the Monastery. Jiří at Prague Castle, from the beginning of the 15th century," he said, listing the reasons why he said people should watch the exhibition.
Also on display will be the Epistle of Peter of Blois, where the semipemaker H (enrico) is depicted in the opening miniature of King Henry II of England. The author of the decoration is most likely the Master of Samson's History, who, in addition to the two volumes of the Václav IV Bible, was also involved in the decoration of a number of other manuscripts. Visitors will also see the Latin collection of John Wycliff's tractualion from the period from about 1411 to 1414.
The library of Wenceslas IV was not retained on Czech territory by a single book. According to the experts, this library was one of the most extensive and also most beautiful book collections in what was then Central Europe, because the young king longed to build a representative library to match the book collections of his French relatives. However, the library died soon after Wenceslas' death. Apparently, it was stolen or destroyed in the conquest of the Hussite Castle. But several codes have been saved. Most of them are now owned by the Austrian National Library.
"We have a number of treasures in our collections and I am glad that they are in a state that allows them to be displayed and made available to the public so-called live and not only in the form of the Manuscriptorium digital library," said the director of the National Library, Martin Kocanda.
On the day of Saturday's national holiday, an exhibition called What Plays Below will also be opened in Klementinum for free, presenting the local archaeological discoveries.
